With full knowledge that it risks making me sound like a complete prat, I guess I have to admit that kind of is what I'm saying. To massively belabour my point, using semicolons to boot: the vast majority of people who visit this site are casual browsers; compared to us folks who make an account and vote regularly on submissions, those guys probably won't be as uber-comfortable with the SCP format and as generally obsessed with reading and writing; I think you need to be very comfortable with the SCP format and have a really good ability to tease out throughlines and interpret complex narratives to properly get what's going on here. Plus, we know that a good half of the users who completed the Community Survey are teenagers, and I'm pretty sure that I personally wouldn't have understood most of this piece if I read it before I turned 17, at least. I'll also say that I don't think you're in any way a better person if you can really  a piece of writing like this. All it means is that, over the course of your life, you got the chance to read a bunch of stuff, and therefore you got a bunch of practice in interpreting tricky writing. Sorry to defend myself so lengthily, but I just wanted to show that, despite appearances, I'm not a total arse. I do a lot of work in teaching, and I guess it's made me a little pessimistic about the average Joe's reading comprehension skills.

I regret my phrasing with the . Stupid hyperbole there, but I'll stand by the basic point.

Also, looks like my prediction about the score was way off. I am prepared to eat 1 (one) slice of humble pie at the now-inevitable centennial.







